Post-Ebola syndrome
-----------
10 Aug 2015: Missionary recounts Ebola fight as both doctor and patient
http://www.pbs.org/newshour/videos/#152862
[ZMapp human patient no. 1 interview -- unlike Texas nurse, he does not report any sequelae. Worth watching. - Mod.JW]

10 Aug 2015: Post-Ebola syndrome: It's not over for Ebola survivors
http://www.irinnews.org/report/101843/post-ebola-syndrome-it-s-not-over-for-ebola-survivors

11 Aug 2015: Even after surviving Ebola, people still remain very sick for months afterwards
http://qz.com/476246/even-after-surviving-ebola-people-still-remain-very-sick-for-months-afterwards/
[According to the National Institute of Health, The long-term effects of Ebola include vision problems, immune system changes, mental disorders, joint pain; diabetes; hypertension, and pregnancy complications. Studies are under way to observe the progress of such symptoms.
The health consequences can lead to economic distress; Ebola-stricken communities often have disabled people who cannot return to work. Information is also limited about how long Ebola lingers as a sexually transmitted disease, and whether women who survive Ebola suffer complications during pregnancy. Representatives from the World Health Organization (WHO), also noted the high risk of mental health consequences, both for those who contracted the disease and those who saw it affect others]

Prevention
--------
12 Aug 2015 Kenya: refuses refuge to 'Ebola' chimps
http://www.news24.com/Green/News/Kenya-refuses-refuge-to-Ebola-chimps-20150812
[Kenya has rejected a request to bring 2 young chimpanzees rescued in Ebola-hit Liberia to a Kenyan wildlife sanctuary due to fears about the deadly virus, the country's top veterinarian said on Wed 12 Aug 2015]

11 Aug 2015: Liberia expands cross-border screening to combat spread of Ebola
http://www.iom.int/news/liberia-expands-cross-border-screening-combat-spread-ebola
[Under a new project funded by USAID's Office of US Foreign Disaster Assistance (OFDA), IOM will work with county health teams and the Ministry of Health Disease Prevention and Control Division to provide key resources, training and mentoring support to major ports of entry and border communities in [8] counties]

9 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: Health boss wants Ebola countries to give games a miss
http://www.newslinesamoa.com/?p=2025
[Ebola-stricken African countries like Sierra Leone will give local health officials major relief if they should decide to miss the Samoa Commonwealth Youth Games next month [Dec 2015]. Sierra Leone's Ministry of Health chief executive officer, Leausa Dr Take Naseri, personally admitted it on Fri [7 Aug 2015]

7 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: Stakeholders identify Ebola challenges in Kailahun
http://allafrica.com/stories/201508101297.html
[Although Kailahun (capital of Kailahun District) was declared Ebola free more than 200 days ago, stakeholders in the eastern district are aware the virus could return. Therefore, in a collaboration with the Social Enterprise for Development Foundation (SEND), they have identified challenges which could undermine their capacity to prevent a recurrence. Therefore, with funds provided by the Department for International Development's Emergency Ebola Response Fund, through Welt Hunger Hilfe, SEND facilitated drafting of the Kailahun Remote Villages Ebola Prevention Project plan, targeting 32 border crossing points.]

12 Aug 2015 West Africa: Handwashing in W African schools protects families from Ebola: UN
http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/26d7028049735f2fa505bffbc39efa26/-
[UNICEF (United Nations Children's Fund) said there had been no reported cases of students or teachers contracting Ebola at a school this year in the 3 worst-hit countries in West Africa]

