Research
--------
24 Jul 2015 [note date] UK: King's Ebola response team say 1/5 positive ebola cases may have been missed: http://goo.gl/DJsoZ4
[King's College London -- King's Ebola response team calls for better diagnostic tests]

10 Aug 2015: Proposed Ebola biobank would strengthen African science
http://www.nature.com/news/proposed-ebola-biobank-would-strengthen-african-science-1.18158
[International public health officials discuss how to maximize research benefits of a widely dispersed collection. For biosafety reasons, Public Health Canada would not reveal where their specimens are being held, other than "West Africa". According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, it is keeping samples both in West Africa and the United States but would not state how many it holds. In December 2015, it shipped 7000 from Sierra Leone to the United States (see Nature http://doi.org/6jm; 2014). However, the agency has come under fire recently for major lapses in biosecurity (see Nature http://doi.org/6jn; 2015), and raised this among a number of potential hurdles to creating a biobank]

Vaccine
-------
11 Aug 2015: News about the success of a new Ebola vaccine may be too good to be true
https://www.rawstory.com/2015/08/news-about-the-success-of-a-new-ebola-vaccine-may-be-too-good-to-be-true
[A detailed analysis of why the 100 per cent efficacy claimed may not be correct. - Mod.JW]

Funding
-------
10 Aug 2015: Guinea's ability to import rice impacted by Ebola outbreak, says FAO
http://oryza.com/23460/guineas-ability-import-more-rice-impacted-ebola-outbreak-says-fao
[The United Nations' Food and Agricultural Organization (FAO) forecasts Guinea's 2015 imported rice requirements to be about 320 000 tons. Guinea's commercial rice imports have been stable at about 300 000 tons. The FAO states the government needs additional resources and international assistance to fulfil the importation of the remaining 20 000 tons needed.]

12 Aug 2015 Liberia: In US Ebola response empty ETUs to expend over USD 5 million
http://allafrica.com/stories/201508120989.html
[Behind the Ganta Methodist Hospital sits an Ebola Treatment Unit which is considered state of the art by experts -- but since its opening in January 2015, the center has not had any confirmed Ebola patients. With no Ebola patients, the center operated by Project Concern International (PCI) has exhausted almost 60 per cent of the USD 5.6 million provided by the US government for its operation. Critics charge that millions of dollars spent by an Ebola treatment center that never had an Ebola patient is unjustifiable, but PCI argues, in an interview with FrontPageAfrica, that though it wasn't receiving Ebola patients, it used the money to strengthen surveillance in Nimba County, and the organization suggests that this intervention could explain why the county remains stable in the Ebola fight thus far reporting zero new cases.]

7 Aug 2015 Liberia: NAYMOTE provides grants to Ebola survivors in Bong County
http://allafrica.com/stories/201508111133.html
[The National Youth Movement for Transparent Elections (NAYMOTE), Partners for Democratic Development, has completed the disbursement of a grant of SLL 25 000 [USD 5.38] each, to 8 Ebola survivors in 4 districts in Bong County. The districts are Jorquelleh, Suakoko, Yellequelleh and Salala. The program is an economic empowerment initiative undertaken by the National Civil Society Ebola Task Force with funding from the Open Society Initiative for West Africa (OSIWA). A little goes a long way in Liberia. - Mod.JW]

10 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: 250 Ebola survivors get clothing support from Caritas Freetown
http://allafrica.com/stories/201508111034.html
[Caritas Freetown, with support from Healey International Relief Foundation and Buddhist Tzu Chi Foundation West Africa, on Wednesday, 5 Aug 2015 provided clothing support to about 250 Ebola survivors. The beneficiaries were predominantly female survivors within the Western Rural District with the gesture coming during a psychosocial workshop.]

